article.description:
Becky Hammon led New York's comeback, scoring
nine of her 12 points in the second half to lead the Liberty past
the Phoenix Mercury 70-64 Wednesday night.
article.headline: Hammon's heroics spark second-half rally
article.linkText: Mercury lose to Liberty, remain winless at MSG
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Every time Becky Hammon touched the ball, the
crowd grew louder.

The Madison Square Garden fans went from cheering to screaming
to just plain shrieking as Hammon led New York's comeback, scoring
nine of her 12 points in the second half to lead the Liberty past
the Phoenix Mercury 70-64 Wednesday night.

The Liberty were in control for much of the game before allowing
Phoenix to build a seven-point lead in the second half. But the
Mercury remained winless in eight games at Madison Square Garden
thanks in no small part to Hammon, who again inspired the Liberty
as a reserve.

"She came in and really sparked them in the second half,"
Phoenix coach John Shumate said. "She basically single-handedly
ignited them, gave them some energy and put fuel back into their
fire."

Adrian Williams led Phoenix (2-10) with 14 points and had 10
rebounds. Tamicha Jackson had 12.

Vickie Johnson led the Liberty with 19 points, and Tari Phillips
had a physical 18 points and 12 rebounds for New York (6-4), but it
was Hammon who woke up the crowd and the Liberty in the second
half.

Of course, she might not have been able to do it without Teresa
Weatherspoon, whose role on the Liberty has decreased recently in
favor of Hammon, her backup.

The two shared the floor at times Wednesday night, but when
Weatherspoon came back in the game with 7:55 to play, she had a
message.

"She just told me. `I'm going to get you going,' " Hammon
said. "Up until that point, I felt like I wasn't getting a lot of
looks."

By that point, the Liberty had already begun to chip into
Phoenix' seven-point advantage, and Hammon scored two straight
baskets to tie the game at 56 with 6:44 to play.

After Phoenix regained the lead briefly, Hammon scored again on
a pass from Weatherspoon to give the Liberty the lead for good at
59-58 with just under five minutes left.

As soon as he saw Weatherspoon feed Hammon, Shumate smacked the
padding around the scorers' table in frustration.

He gave it an even more emphatic whack two minutes later, when
Hammon scored again to make it 63-60 with 3:08 left, sending the
announced crowd of 10,021 over the edge. The fans weren't as happy,
however, when Liberty coach Richie Adubato lifted Hammon for the
taller Crystal Robinson with 1:21 to play.

"It feels nice they appreciate what you're doing out there,"
Hammon said. "I know they didn't mean disrespect to anyone."

Anna DeForge, a starter for Phoenix after two seasons out of the
WNBA, led the Mercury's short-lived rally after halftime.

She opened the second half with a pair of 3-pointers, and scored
all of her 13 points in the half as Phoenix took a 45-44 lead with
about 12 minutes to play. The Mercury led 56-49 with 8:44 to go,
but Phillips scored a putback and a free throw before Hammon tied
it.

"They made us work for this game tonight," Phillips said.
"I'm very proud of our effort."

Phoenix went ahead briefly with 8:50 to play in the first, when
Edwina Brown's jumper gave it an 18-17 lead. But New York regained
control with 12 straight points. The Mercury didn't make another
basket until Jackson's 3-pointer 39.3 seconds before halftime.

Johnson sank a shot at the first-half buzzer to give the Liberty
a 35-23 lead.<
^Notes: @ Weatherspoon started for New York, but scored just one
point. She had nine assists. 'Spoon played 27 minutes to Hammon's
23. ... Williams tied a career high with four steals. ... New York
F Tamika Whitmore missed the game with a sprained right foot.
Whitmore was injured last week against Charlotte. ... Elena
Baranova had 12 points and eight rebounds for the Liberty. ...
Johnson's first-half buzzer beater was upheld by video review.
